Author: @kattz9051
Comment: It actually is helpful to stopping the virus, but from a social standpoint rather than a scientific one. Without an actual name people were either actually calling it Coronavirus as Its name, not a placeholder, or nicknaming it the China virus.  It seems harmless enough but in the first case, people were associating Coronaviruses (the group not the covid-19) with the Coronavirus and causing confusion/misinformation. Both of which are dangerous during a time of an epidemic and possible pandemic.  The bigger one imo, is the latter case where people were calling this the China virus or anything of the like that puts China or Asia in the title. This sparked issues of racism as Asians (not even just ethnically Chinese) started being discriminated against within their countries despite having never been to China, much less Wuhan. The likelihood of them having the disease is about the same as anyone else in their country yet because of the way they look and the nickname of the virus, would treat them poorly. I have a friend from the Philippines (has no Chinese family and has never been to China) who said that she was eating and talking on the phone while sitting on a park bench. The food went down the wrong throat so she coughed. As a result, the people walking by her stared at her in horror and lifted up their shirts to cover their mouths/noses while moving past.  So while it seems like it's not a big deal that they finally gave this a name, it somewhat is. In fact I wish they did it sooner.
